HEADWORD: Isopiestic
<hw>I`so*pi*es"tic</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos>
<ety>[<ets>Iso-</ets> + Gr. <?/ to press.]</ety>
<fld>(Thermodynamics)</fld> <def>Having equal pressure.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Isopiestic lines</b></col>, <cd>lines showing, in a
diagram, the relations of temperature and volume, when the elastic force
is constant; -- called also <altname>isobars</altname>.</cd></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

